	id="Illu_SubSequence">
	<title>Subsequence: Illustration</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>Given a sequence <latex>(a_n)</latex> of real numbers, we obtain a subsequence by forming a composite</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\NNr \overset{n}{\longrightarrow} \NNr \overset{a}{\longrightarrow} \RNr</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>Thus we obtain a new sequence <latex>(b_i)</latex> of real numbers, with</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex magnify="yes">b_0:=a_{n(0)}=:a_{n_0},\quad b_1:=a_{n(1)}=:a_{n_1},\quad b_2:=b_{n(2)}=:a_{n_2},\quad \dots</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>In the graphic below this process gives</para>
			<figure>
				<img src="ims/SubSequence.png"></img><!-- svg available -->
			</figure>
			<ol>
				<li><para><latex magnify="yes">b_0 = a_{n_0} = a_3</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex magnify="yes">b_1 = a_{n_1} = a_4</latex></para></li>
				<li><para><latex magnify="yes">b_2 = a_{n_2} = a_7</latex></para></li>
				<li><para>etc.</para></li>
			</ol>
		</block>
		<block>
			<para>Thus we may think of a subsequence of <latex>(a_n)</latex> as the outcome of</para>
			<ol>
				<li><para>Omitting some members of the original sequence</para></li>
				<li><para>Re-indexing the remaining sequence elements, as described above.</para></li>
			</ol>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>